  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">The anonymous author of the Contest of Homer and Hesiod is unknown. The work is a fictional prose narrative from the Roman Imperial period, specifically dated to the 2nd century CE. It elaborates on an older tradition, noted by Herodotus, of a poetic competition between Homer and Hesiod. The compiler likely worked within the cultural milieu of the Second Sophistic, a period of revived interest in archaic Greek culture.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The sole identified work is the Contest of Homer and Hesiod. This prose narrative describes a fictional poetic competition between the two legendary poets, incorporating biographical anecdotes and samples of their verse.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The Contest is a significant document in the history of literary biography and the reception of early Greek poetry. It preserves an early version of the &quot;lives&quot; of Homer and Hesiod, blending legend and fabricated excerpts. Influential in antiquity and later periods, it reflects ancient debates about the poets&#x27; chronology and merit while exemplifying the literary tastes of the Roman Imperial era.</p>\n</div>",
